        <h3 class="article__heading">Challenge</h3>

        <p>The product team at HBR.org came to us with a problem. They have so much content by way of articles, videos, and podcasts that they believe their subscribers have a hard time finding the pieces that apply directly to them. On their site, subscribers are given a search tool that‚Äôs not intuitive or cognizant of their desired areas of growth. They have a mobile app that doesn‚Äôt solve this problem, but instead emphasizes the point that they have trouble connecting subscribers with the content that interests them. Therefore, they wanted to answer the following question: <strong>Do our subscribers want content curated just for them?</strong></p>

        <p>They defined their business challenge, but they also needed a way to align their various teams on an idea. This curation challenge made its way through various internal groups at HBR, from marketing to editorial to product. Everyone had done work on this particular problem, and it was important that they could come together and agree on a potential solution to try.</p>

