        <p>I knew a Product Design Sprint was needed to get the different teams in a room to gain consensus on an idea and agree upon a path forward. I also knew that I needed to act as a meditator of sorts. A facilitator acting as a moderator who would encourage usually silent contributors to speak up, and to keep conversations moving and tangent-lite.</p>

        <p>The HBR team showed up on Monday as a group of 16. That plus me and another designer brought the total to 18. Their roles varied, from C-suite (Editor, Creative Director, Publisher), to IC (individual contributors, such as Product and UX designers). So many different roles, so many different perspectives and experiences. I knew it was crucial to keep them talking to each other, to encourage them to tell their stories and share their own ideas and expectations.</p>

        <h3 class="article__heading">Process</h3>

        <p>Being that the group for this Sprint was almost 4x the ideal size, I made adjustments to the format that featured smaller break out groups for activities such as researching competitors and creating storyboards. I also stretched the Understand phase out to two days instead of the usual one, to account for an incredible information download, lots of conversation, and of course, more breaks.</p>

