        <p>We held eight interviews with HBR subscribers where we asked background questions for our research, as well as received feedback on our prototype. After the first four interviews, we iterated on our prototype to address any common questions or pitfalls that caused any hiccups or confusions. After we completed the final round of interviews, we synthesized our feedback and presented our findings and recommendations to the HBR team at large.</p>

        <p>Overall, the main idea of the prototype was well-received, but the team needed to continue iterating on ways to execute that idea. Our users responded positively to the idea of getting curated content in different formats. There was more exploration to be done around on onboarding, user preferences, and notifications.</p>

        <p>We ultimately made the recommendation that they narrow their focus even more to a singular user type (like a first-time manager), because our broad onboarding questions were difficult to relate to and often missed the mark. We also encouraged the team to look beyond content, and see how else they could address common pain points we heard in our interviews around mentorship and networking.</p>

        <p>The HBR was so happy with the work we did over these three weeks, and felt a renewed sense of collaboration and connectedness within their team, across the different departments. They truly are an incredible group of people to work with, and we were so happy to have the opportunity to work with them again the following year.

