        <div class="takeaways__content">
          <h4>‚úÖ Surface sprint goals</h4>
          <p>When presented with the task to facilitate a large group of people (in this case it was 18), be clear on who is in your group, what their existing dynamics are, and what your goals are.</p>
          <p>In this Sprint, the ultimate goal was to facilitate conversations across different departments to ultimately gain consensus on an idea. The idea itself wasn‚Äôt the most important thing. It was the opportunity to share ideas in a safe space, feel heard, and to get on the same page as a unified team.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="takeaways__content">
          <h4>üåç Consider international users</h4>
          <p>We interviewed users from all over the globe: Africa, Canada, Germany, US, and Sweden. Being that everyone had different remote capabilities, we agreed upon video conferencing software before we met for our interviews. We also found that the easiest way to compensate everyone for their time was through digital Amazon gift cards. You just need to ask which Amazon site is convenient for them, whether it be .com, .ca, .co.uk, etc.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="takeaways__content">
          <h4>üí• Breakup large groups</h4>
          <p>When facilitating for a large group, my general rule of thumb is less talking, more writing. I encourage activities where people can individually brainstorm to ultimately present to the group at large. This is especially inclusive for those who struggle to speak up in large group settings.</p>
          <p>I also encourage breakout groups with no more than three people. The larger the group gets, the harder it is to collaborate and participate. And also, consider dot voting to be your new best friend. It‚Äôs been the single-most effective tool I‚Äôve used to help large groups narrow focus on a single idea.</p>
